    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-11-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-11-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="35" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                <head>No. 34.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hall</persName> to
                            Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                    States Legation in Central America</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-11-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 4, 1885</date>.
                            (Received November 29.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">441.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * I have the honor to inform you that on
                        the 29th ultimo I received a telegram from Mr. Leavitt, our consul at
                        Managua, stating that President Cardenas had gained positive information
                        that two vessels, with troops and arms, were in the Gulf of Fonseca
                        preparing to invade Nicaragua. This report was confirmed the next day by a
                        telegram from Honduras.* * * I have since learned that the expedition
                        effected a landing in Nicaraguan territory, and is now in the department of
                        Chinandega; that Nicaragua is again under martial law, but that thus <pb facs="0133" n="49" xml:id="pg_49"/> far there had been no general
                        uprising in the country in favor of the revolution, as the invaders
                        expected. There is little doubt, however, that unless the Government should
                        succeed in suppressing the movement promptly, the country will have entered
                        into a long period of convulsion and bloodshed.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HENRY C. HALL.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
